<font color="#FF0000">TO CHARLES</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jan  4 23:12:55 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Charles,<br><br>
In my earlier response to you I thought that you meant that the government which permitted protest was the American government. Are you saying that the Diem government allowed protests and basic freedom?<br><br>
I agree that a considerable number of Vietnamese didn't want to be ruled by the communists. A great many didn't want to be ruled by Diem either - mainly the Buddhists, and those who sympathised with the Viet Minh. A referendum would have been a solution.<br><br>
Diem instituted the Denunciation of Communists Campaign in 1955 and it lasted until 1957. Thousands of veterans who were members of the resistance in the south against the French were killed without a hearing. Many of their family members, and family members of veterans who chose to go north were also killed or sent to reeducation camps. The litmus test, oftentimes, was if a person was opposed to the French, then it had to follow that the person was opposed the Diem family also. 50 to 100 thousand Vietnamese were sent to reeducation camps - thousands of them dying from disease and torture. Diem furthered the problem by causing scorn and resentment among people who weren't even communists because of his ignorance of the high regard average Vietnamese in the south had for those who fought against the French. <br><br>
In May of 1963 Diem issued a decree that Buddhists were not allowed to fly the Buddhist flag on Buddha's birthday.  Is that representative of what you term, Basic Freedom?<br><br>
As for us denying the French at their &quot;critical moment at Dien Bien Phu&quot;, are you meaning the tactical nukes? Doesn't the fact that we were subsidizing France's war with its colony at the tune of a Billion a year count for anything? Nukes to preserve French Colonialism? Then what?<br><br>
I am not sure I understand what you mean by the following:<br><br>
&lt;You have brought up a matter that many veterans bring up to<br>
explain why they decided the war was &quot;wrong&quot;.The<br>
justification for protest generally involves the unnecessary loss of Americans´lives due to the incompetence of the military services, grave injustices perpetrated by military or civilian officials, deliberate deceit of the public by elected officials and civil servants, and profiteering at the expense of the fighting men. The basic evils in the government that permitted these things to happen would have<br>
existed whether or not the United States had gone to war in<br>
Vietnam. The fact that the war was fought brought many of these things to light. Did the protest movement help bring about reform? I think that the opposite may have been true...<br><br>
There is a basic difference between an unjust cause and a just cause lost through bad leadership and corrupt institutions. Proclaiming a lost cause to be unjust absolves the corrupt institutions from blame and permits many criminals to go unprosecuted.&gt;<br><br>
Could you please explain?
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


